@ThinkingandTinkering If a person simply put it into a metal paint can with a hose barb plumbed into the lid, and attached it to another such sealed can full of calcium chloride [ice melter] and then put the can full of plastic pulp out in the sun some place, [preferably put the can with the CaCl2 some place cool, like a camping ice chest filled with ice] then the hygroscopic nature of CaCl2, accompanied by the thermal difference between the 2 cans would drive a lot of moisture off over a day's time.

Mason jars would do the same thing, but they don't usually come as large as metal paint cans [mason jars typically go up to about 1/2 gallons imperial or 2 liters metric, while metal paint pails come in as much as 5 gallons imperial or 18 liters metric], and they conduct heat less efficiently because of the nature of glass.

Also, metal cans can take more rough handling than glass.
